@Node "CONCEPT" "CONCEPT"
@Toc "Main"

The concepts behind X·Pegs
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    I am constantly needing fresh, high quality, high resolution images
 for various projects, but my meager 12 year old Amiga doesn't want to
 spend its precious time searching through WWW pages, BBS archives and
 such for 'the right picture'.  Photo-CDs are great, but every conver-
 sion program I've come across either wants hordes of memory, or is
 unstable, or both!  So one day I began converting these high quality
 images into a more practical format.

    X·Pegs is simply a collection of high quality, JPeg compressed
 images.  Handy indexes (HTML & AmigaGuide® complete with thumbnail
 mini-images) provide an easy way to find the image you want.


@EndNode
@Node "SYSREQ" "SYSREQ"
@Toc "Main"

System Requirements
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    X·Pegs has no specific requirements.  :)

    The installer script requires AmigaDOS 2.x or greater and
 ReqTools.library.

    The HTML & AmigaGuide® indexes requires AmigaDOS3.x (for the JPeg
 datatype and MultiView.  If your machine doesn't meet these require-
 ments, you can still view the table of contents.  Simply double-click
 on the 'TOC' icon of your choice.

    X·Pegs does not require a special processor, but of course the
 faster CPUs make life easier.  A complex calculation is required for
 JPeg de-compression, so a "base" 68000 based machine will be slow.
 An 030 or greater is recommended.


@EndNode
@Node "INSTALL" "INSTALL"
@Toc "Main"

Installation
~~~~~~~~~~~~

    To install X·Pegs to your hard drive, simply double-click on the
 install icon.  You will be asked where you want the archive to be
 placed.  Subsequent image packs will ask you the same question.


@EndNode
@Node "HTML" "HTML"
@Toc "Main"

The HTML index
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    The HTML index provides a simple way to find the image you want.
 Load the index into the browser as a LOCAL file, and click a
 thumbnail image to see the full image.  At this point, you might
 choose to save the image (save source) to somewhere else for use
 with a paint program.

    As all thumbnail image are in 4096 color HAM mode, users with ECS
 Amigas may not be satisfied with this method.  Use the AmigaGuide®
 index instead.


@EndNode
